The world born on September 11th
NEW YORK – This week marks the 20th anniversary of the terrorist attacks on September 11, 2001, in the United States.
On that day, 19 terrorists took control of four civilian airplanes, hijacked two of the planes and flew them into the World Trade Center towers in New York, struck the Pentagon with a third, and then caused a fourth plane to crash in Pennsylvania after several passengers physically prevented the terrorists from reaching their target, which many believe was the White House or another U.S. government building in Washington, D.C.
All the air pirates were from the Middle East, and 15 from Saudi Arabia.
All had been trained in Afghanistan, and four in American flight schools, as part of a planned, organized, and carried-out operation by Al-Qaida (the "base"), a terrorist group led by Osama bin Laden.
By the end of the day, 2,977 innocent men, women, and children were reported dead, and over 6,000 were injured.
Most were Americans, although citizens from more than a hundred other countries also lost their lives.
Many at the time feared that September 11 had ushered in an era defined by global terrorism.
Indeed, other attacks carried out by Al-Qaida followed, including several bombings on trains in Madrid in March 2004, then the attack carried out on the public transport system in London in July 2005.
Terrorists affiliated with the Islamic State (IS) also killed 32 people at Brussels Airport in March 2016, and carried out a series of smaller-scale attacks (often using vehicles to run over pedestrians).
For all that, neither the United States nor any of its allies have ever suffered an attack of comparable scale to those of September 11 – which are without parallel.
It is therefore worth asking: Beyond the immediate losses, what difference did September 11 make?
Has history changed, and if so, to what extent?
Many reasons explain why the terrorists were not able to carry out other major attacks.
After the U.S. invasion of Afghanistan, Al-Qaida lost its sanctuary.
Almost every government in the world has implemented security procedures making it more difficult for potential terrorists to access airports and airplanes.
States have significantly strengthened their intelligence, police, and military capabilities in order to minimize risks and counter threats.
They have also developed mutual cooperation, terrorism being one of the few areas in which states often at odds are willing and ready to work together to a significant extent.
There is also now a broad consensus on what constitutes terrorism – the use of armed force by individuals and groups against civilians for political purposes – as well as a degree of support for the principle that governments cannot make a distinction between terrorists and those who provide them sanctuary and support.
The era when individuals and groups willing to kill in the name of their cause were romanticized as freedom fighters is over.
It is not a matter of asserting that terrorism has ceased to claim tens of thousands of lives each year.
However, nearly all attacks occur in the Middle East, Africa, and South Asia within the context of ongoing conflicts (primarily in Iraq, Syria, Afghanistan, Libya, Somalia, Nigeria, Pakistan, and Yemen), as opposed to isolated attacks of the September 11 type against major powers.
Terrorism is becoming increasingly localized and decentralized.
It is also resilient: the capture or elimination of a terrorist organization's leader does not necessarily mean the end of the group.
Al-Qaida, for example, survived the elimination of Bin Laden by U.S. special forces in Pakistan, nearly ten years after the September 11 attacks.
It is therefore not surprising that terrorism persists, with no solution to the problem on the horizon.
The possibility of a new September 11 cannot be ruled out either, although the U.S. government has recently stated that the "most urgent terrorist threat" to the country exists domestically.
As the Provisional Irish Republican Army formulated after its failed 1984 attempt to assassinate British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, "Today, we haven't had luck, but remember that it only takes one chance."
You will always need to have it.
The danger lies in the fact that one day, terrorists may acquire nuclear material, or manage to produce and use a biological or chemical weapon, in which case terrorism could determine the era.
For now, that is not the case.
September 11 marked a historical turning point, with a profound impact on American foreign policy over the past two decades.
If the attacks did not lead to an era of global terrorism, they did indeed give rise to the famous global war on terror, with major consequences for the behavior of the United States around the world, the image of America in the eyes of the world, and the way in which many Americans came to view their country's foreign policy.
The saga began in Afghanistan.
Shortly after the September 11 attacks, the United States presented the Taliban, who then controlled the Afghan government, with a choice: hand over the Al-Qaida leaders responsible for organizing the September 11 attacks as they were about to leave the country, or risk endangering their rule.
After the Taliban refused to hand over Al-Qaida leaders, U.S. intelligence and military forces collaborated with an loosely structured Afghan tribal confederation called the Northern Alliance to overthrow the Taliban.
The United States helped form a successor government that took control of most of the country.
This control has never been total, nor uncontested.
Many individuals loyal to the Taliban and Al-Qaida took refuge in the neighboring Pakistan, where they gradually regained their strength and resumed military operations against the government that had replaced them.
From their side, the United States did not work sufficiently to build an Afghan army, reduce corruption, and deprive the Taliban of sanctuary in Pakistan.
Instead, America strengthened its own presence and military operations in Afghanistan, becoming essentially a partner of the government in its civil war.
At its peak, the U.S. intervention in Afghanistan mobilized more than 100,000 American soldiers.
Over twenty years, the cost of the operations has reached more than $2,000 billion, for the loss of more than 2,300 American lives, and tens of thousands among the Afghans.
The effort was both excessive and insufficient.
The U.S. presence deprived the Afghan government of much of its legitimacy and sparked opposition to the United States, while the Taliban proved more persistent than America, which by 2020 had lost all will to fight in a conflict destined to end only in an indefinite stalemate.
The global war on terrorism also led the United States to go to war in Iraq.
The question remains open as to whether President George W. Bush would have acted militarily had September 11 not occurred.
The attacks certainly reinforced his tendency to signal to the world that the United States was not, as President Richard Nixon had formulated during the Vietnam War, a "helpless and pitiful giant."
This led some members of the administration (notably Vice President Dick Cheney) to refuse the risk of terrorists acquiring weapons of mass destruction, which Iraqi leader Saddam Hussein apparently possessed (which, according to most participants, was not the case).
Other members intended to spread democracy in Iraq and then throughout the Middle East, considering that this approach was not only feasible but would also make the region much less likely to produce and support terrorists.
La war in Iraq, launched in March 2003, did not unfold as the Bush administration and numerous members of Congress (including Joe Biden, then a senator) and world leaders who had approved it had hoped or expected.
The United States were not prepared for most of the events to come.
The military victories achieved at first indeed allowed the government to be ousted, but quickly gave way to widespread unrest as well as violent civil war.
The decision to dissolve the Iraqi army and exclude many Iraqis associated with the previous regime from government jobs worsened an already chaotic situation.
More fundamentally, Iraq, like Afghanistan, has demonstrated the limits of what military power can achieve at a reasonable cost and within reasonable timeframes.
In the end, the United States were forced to increase their military presence, bringing it to nearly 170,000 troops, in order to protect the besieged successor government in Baghdad.
A certain degree of stability was achieved, but at a considerable cost.
The United States spent at least as much in Iraq as in Afghanistan, but at a much heavier human cost: over 4,000 American soldiers killed, a significantly higher number of wounded, and a surge in suicide rates among U.S. military personnel (both in Iraq and Afghanistan).
This total also excludes deaths among private contractors and Iraqis, for whom estimates vary widely, but whose number is certainly in the hundreds of thousands.
The war in Iraq also weakened the United States in other respects.
No evidence has ever demonstrated Iraq's involvement in the September 11 attacks, and America's reputation suffered when the argument for a military intervention without UN approval—aimed at eliminating Saddam's weapons of mass destruction—proved to be based on no real foundation.
The images of American soldiers abusing Iraqi prisoners have further tarnished the country's reputation.
In addition, an Iraq at war with itself has become synonymous with an Iran emerging as the most powerful country in the region (or one of the two most powerful if one considers Israel).
Since the war, Iran has strengthened its influence over Iraq, Syria, Yemen, and Lebanon.
Iraq and Afghanistan have also been revealed as two major strategic distractions.
While the United States was deeply involved in the Middle East and South Asia, regions lacking major powers and economic dynamism, the geopolitical balance shifted against the United States, both in Europe and in East Asia, due to the emergence of a more aggressive Russia and a stronger, more assertive China.
The global war on terrorism could not and has not provided the United States with a compass in its approach to foreign policy toward a renewed rivalry among major powers.
The wars fought in the aftermath of September 11 also led to significant domestic consequences for the United States.
They shook the confidence of a country that had emerged from the Cold War strong with a historically unprecedented dominant power, and undermined the national unity that had emerged immediately after the attacks.
The costs and failures associated with these wars have also fueled opposition to a major and sustained global role for the United States, giving rise to a new isolationist trend.
In the same way, this bellicosity, associated with the global financial crisis of 2007-2009 and its economic repercussions, has seriously impacted American confidence in elites, thus stimulating the rise of a populist sentiment that, among other consequences, contributed to the rise of Donald Trump.
The United States today is more divided than ever domestically, and less and less willing to pursue this form of active foreign policy that characterized it since the end of the Second World War, and which has largely benefited the Americans as well as many others.
Looking back, we can now consider September 11 as a harbinger of what was to come: less the globalization of terrorism than the terrors of globalization.
The attacks conveyed the message that distance and borders mattered little in the global age.
Nothing remains local for very long anymore, whether it be terrorists born in the Middle East and trained in Afghanistan, or the effects of a global financial crisis that originated from poor American financial management.
We are all currently facing a pandemic virus that has killed millions of people since its emergence in China in December 2019.
Fires, droughts, floods, storms, and heatwaves that devastate many regions of the world are the consequence of climate change, itself the cumulative effect of human activity that releases unsustainable amounts of heat-trapping greenhouse gases into the atmosphere.
The era initiated by recent events comes to a close, marking the 20th anniversary of the U.S. intervention in the country.
Twenty years ago, the Taliban were quickly expelled from power; in recent weeks, they have regained it just as easily.
It is too early to know whether the Taliban will resume their old ways by becoming a terrorist sanctuary again, and whether terrorists around the world will take pride in their victory over America and its allies.
What we do know, on the other hand, is that terrorism remains a characteristic of our world.
It will not define the future, but will remain one of the visible aspects of a globalization that has already determined it.
